				\begin{document}$$\upbeta = 10^{ - 2}\upbeta_{\rm N} \text{I}/\text{aB}$$\end{document}where I is the current in Megamps, a is the minor radius in meters, and B is the toroidal field in teslas. Their calculations gave a value for βN, and from this β could be determined. If the plasma had no wall stabilization, they found a maximum stable βN of about 2.5 or a little greater; and with strong wall stabilization, it might be as large as 5.

